<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  1 23:41:28 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
<br><br>
My first trip to the Wall was two years ago, Memorial Day weekend.  I went there knowing there was a small chance my ex-fiance would be there selling his book.  What I found was a magical place, a Wall that sent me through nearly 200,000 strangers and a hard rain that I have come to expect now, to find the man I was looking for in less than 1/2 hr.  Since then I have been to the Wall 4 four times.  I have met many good people, and even a few &quot;wannabes&quot; who have made me more cynical, but not taken away the respect that I have for Veterans.  Each time I travel to The Wall, I experience something magical there.  I am absolutely convinced that the spirits of those young men and women are there, touching and healing the scars of the living.  The Wall is more a church than many churches.  It is a place of goodness, of souls grieving and healing, and of magic.  The people who go there, many of whom return again and again, are making an American pilgramage.  Amazing... And amazing how the Wall will not let even the ttourists leave untouched.  Even the Vietnamese make the pilgramage, and there is nothing so telling as seeing two Veterans who were once enemies nod their heads to each other in quiet respect that does not care for old hatreds.<br><br>
One more thing... for those Vets who have said they were unable to handle going...  when and if you are ready, know that there are many there who will provide the support you need in the way you need it.  The living are there, quietly keeping their eyes out for anyone who might need them, and the souls of the names are there.  Believe me, you will know them, know they love you, and that they want you to be happy.<br><br>
If you see a tall redheaded poet barbecuing on 20th street, stop and say hello.  That's me!   &lt;smile&gt;<br><br>
